definition.value: An organic anion that is the conjugate base of digitoxin resulting from the deprotonation of furanone moiety; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of digoxigenin resulting from the deprotonation of the furanone moiety; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of ouabain resulting from the deprotonation of the furanone moiety; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of ouabagenin resulting from the deprotonation of the furanone moiety; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-benzofuran consisting of phthalide having a butylidene group at the 3-position.

A quinolone that is 4-quinolone substituted at positions 1, 3, 5, 6 and 7 by ethyl, carboxy, amino, fluorine, and cyclohexylamino groups, respectively. It can directly bind to and block the transcription activity of the active forkhead box protein O1 (Foxo1), but not the Ser256-phosphorylated form. It induces cell death and growth arrest in Burkitt lymphoma cell lines at low concentrations.
An S-conjugate L-cysteinylglycine zwitterion substituted by a benzyl group; major species at pH 7.3.
An S-conjugate L-cysteine zwitterion substituted by a benzyl group; major species at pH 7.3.
An S-conjugate L-cysteinylglycine zwitterion substituted by a (1-hydroxy-3-methylhexan-3-yl) group; major species at pH 7.3.
An S-conjugate L-cysteine zwitterion substituted by a (1-hydroxy-3-methylhexan-3-yl) group; major species at pH 7.3.
A perillyl alcohol in which the chiral centre has R configuration.
Any inhibitor that acts on forkhead box protein O1 (FOXO1).
A 2-methylamino-1-phenylpropan-1-one that has (S)-configuration.
An organic group that is any protein residue cross-linked with an abasic site of DNA.

A peptide hormone which consists of two polypeptide chains, A- and B- chains which are linked together by disulfide bonds. The amino acid sequence of insulin varies across species and certain segments of the molecule are highly conserved. In most species, the A chain consists of 21 amino acids and the B chain consists of 30 amino acids. In mammals, insulin is synthesised in the pancreas within the beta cells whereas in certain species of fish, the insulin-producing tissue is uniquely located in separate structures called Brockmann bodies.
Major species at pH 7.3.
A cysteine zwitterion derived from D-cysteine by transfer of a proton from each of the carboxy groups to the amino groups.
Any EC 1.2.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor aldehyde/oxo group with NAD(+) or NADP(+) as acceptor) inhibitor that inhibits the action of aspartate-semialdehyde dehydrogenase (EC 1.2.1.11).
A diterpene that is 3-methylidenehexadec-1-ene substituted at positions 7, 11 and 15 by a methyl group.
The anhydrous form of the calcium salt of mupirocin. The dihydrate form is used as an antibacterial drug for the treatment of skin infections.

An amino-acid residue that is formed when the carboxy group of any amino acid (where R is the side chain) undergoes a cyclodehydration reaction with a neighboring L-serine amino acid in a protein, resulting in the formation of a 2-oxazoline moiety.

An amino-acid residue that is formed when the carboxy group of any amino acid (where R is the side chain) undergoes a cyclodehydration reaction with a neighbouring L-serine amino acid in a protein, resulting in the formation of a 2-oxazoline ring which is dehydrogenated to the corresponding 1,3-oxazole moiety.

An amino-acid residue that is formed when the carboxy group of any amino acid (where R is the side chain) undergoes a cyclodehydration reaction with a neighboring L-cysteine amino acid in a protein, resulting in the formation of a 2-thiazoline moiety.

An amino-acid residue that is formed when the carboxy group of any amino acid (where R is the side chain) undergoes a cyclodehydration reaction with a neighboring L-cysteine amino acid in a protein, resulting in the formation of a 2-thiazoline ring which is dehydrogenated to the corresponding 1,3-thiazole moiety.

An amino-acid residue that is formed when the carboxy group of any amino acid (where R is the side chain) undergoes a cyclodehydration reaction with a neighboring L-threonine amino acid in a protein, resulting in the formation of a 5-methyl oxazoline moiety.

An amino-acid residue that is formed when the carboxy group of any amino acid (where R is the side chain) undergoes a cyclodehydration reaction with a neighboring L-threonine amino acid in a protein, resulting in the formation of a 5-methyl oxazoline ring which is dehydrogenated to the corresponding 5-methyl-1,3-oxazole moiety.
A gallate ester obtained by the formal condensation of gallic acid with methanol. It exhibits anti-oxidant, anti-tumor, anti-microbial and anti-inflammatory properties.

An aryl beta-D-glucoside that is phloretin attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 4' via a glycosidic linkage. It is isolated from the leaves of the Chinese sweet tea Lithocarpus polystachyus and exhibits significant anti-hyperglycemic, anti-oxidative and anti-inflammatory properties.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains a total of 22 carbon atoms and 6 double bonds.
A monoacylglycerol in which the acyl group contains a total of 16 carbons and 5 double bonds.
alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-D-Glcp6S in which the anomeric configuration of the 6-O-sulfo-D-glucose residue at the reducing end is beta.
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of the 5-hydroxy group of norrubrofusarin. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of ustilaginoidin A, obtained by deprotonation of the two hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 5'. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3.
C41H78NO8P
